###This appears to be a bug!

According to the Apps Script Documentation, other than for the Contacts service:

&gt; Dates used elsewhere in App Script use JavaScript&#39;s standard [Date](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date) object.

Using the JavaScript console of your web browser, you can see that parsing `08-09-2019 10:59 AM` into `new Date(&quot;08-09-2019 10:59 AM&quot;);` returns correctly:
```lang-text
Fri Aug 09 2019 10:59:00 GMT+0200 (Central European Summer Time)
```
As a result, I have filed a bug on Google&#39;s Issue Tracker detailing this. You can find the issue report [here](http://issuetracker.google.com/issues/143065963) and you can click the  in the top left to let Google know that you are experiencing the issue too.

###Workaround:
For now, as long as your dates are all of the same format, you can convert the date into a format that is defined in the Date Constructor of the [MDN web docs](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date):
```lang-js
function parseDate(date) {
  var parts = date.split(&quot; &quot;);
  var datePart = parts[0].split(&quot;-&quot;);
  var timePart = parts[1];
  var amPm = parts[2];
  
  if (amPm == &quot;PM&quot;) {
    var temp = timePart.split(&quot;:&quot;);
    timePart = (parseInt(temp[0]) + 12).toString() + &quot;:&quot; + temp[1];
  }
  return new Date(datePart[2] + &quot;-&quot; + datePart[0] + &quot;-&quot; + datePart[1] + &quot;T&quot; + timePart + &quot;:00&quot;);
}
```

###Usage:
Instead of using
```lang-js
fileDate = new Date(fileSheet.getRange(2, dateCol, 1, 1).getValue());
```
You can use:
```lang-js
fileDate = parseDate(fileSheet.getRange(2, dateCol, 1, 1).getValue());
```

###References: 
 - [Class `DateField` of Apps Script](https://developers.google.com/apps-script/reference/contacts/date-field)
 - [`Date` object - MDN Web Docs](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date)

